            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this Vermont income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your
                <strong>Vermont state personal income tax</strong> using the
                current VT tax brackets and a simplified model of deductions and
                credits. It is designed for quick planning and education, not
                for filing your return.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Vermont income tax brackets (2024 example)</h3>
              <p>
                Vermont uses a <strong>progressive</strong> tax system:
                different portions of your taxable income are taxed at different
                rates. For illustration, this calculator uses representative
                2024‑style brackets for single filers:
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <strong>Single filer – sample Vermont brackets</strong>
                <ul class="mt-2">
                  <li>3.35% on the first $45,000 of taxable income</li>
                  <li>6.60% on income from $45,001 to $110,000</li>
                  <li>7.60% on income from $110,001 to $200,000</li>
                  <li>8.75% on income over $200,000</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-2">
                  Brackets for married filing jointly, married filing
                  separately, and head of household are scaled versions of these
                  thresholds. Always confirm current official tables with the
                  Vermont Department of Taxes.
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>The calculator:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Takes your <strong>Vermont income</strong> (based on federal
                  AGI plus VT adjustments).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts either a <strong>standard deduction</strong>, your
                  <strong>itemized deductions</strong>, or no deductions (your
                  choice).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Applies the VT tax brackets for your
                  <strong>filing status</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts any <strong>Vermont tax credits</strong> you enter.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. Formula for Vermont tax in each bracket</h3>
              <p>For each bracket, the tax is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  If your taxable income is between limits \(L\) and \(U\) with
                  rate \(r\), then the tax from that bracket is:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Tax}_{\text{bracket}} = \max\bigl(0,\
                  \min(\text{Taxable Income}, U) - L\bigr) \times r \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Total Vermont tax before credits is the
                  <strong>sum</strong> of the tax from all brackets up to your
                  income level.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Effective vs. marginal Vermont tax rate</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective VT tax rate</strong> = \(\text{Total VT tax}
                  \div \text{Taxable income}\). This is your overall average
                  rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal VT tax rate</strong> = the rate on your
                  <strong>last dollar</strong> of income (the bracket you are
                  in).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Your marginal rate is what matters most when you ask, “If I earn
                one more dollar, how much Vermont tax will I pay on it?”
              </p>

              <h2>What you need to use this Vermont tax calculator</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your expected
                  <strong>federal adjusted gross income (AGI)</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Any major
                  <strong>Vermont additions or subtractions</strong> to AGI
                  (e.g., certain interest, Social Security adjustments).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Whether you’ll take the <strong>standard deduction</strong> or
                  <strong>itemize</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rough amounts of any <strong>Vermont tax credits</strong> you
                  qualify for.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is an <strong>educational estimate</strong>, not a filing
                  tool.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> handle every Vermont‑specific
                  rule (phase‑outs, special credits, part‑year residency, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  For official guidance, always refer to the
                  <a
                    href="https://tax.vermont.gov/individuals/personal-income-tax"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    >Vermont Department of Taxes</a
                  >
                  or a qualified tax professional.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Vermont income tax</h2>

              <h3>Is Vermont a high income tax state?</h3>
              <p>
                Vermont’s top marginal rates are relatively high compared with
                many states, but your
                <strong>effective rate</strong> may be much lower once
                deductions and credits are applied. This calculator helps you
                see your own effective rate, not just the top bracket.
              </p>

              <h3>Does Vermont tax Social Security benefits?</h3>
              <p>
                Vermont may exempt some or all Social Security benefits
                depending on your income level. This calculator lets you
                approximate your total VT tax, but for precise treatment of
                Social Security you should follow the official Vermont
                worksheets or use professional software.
              </p>

              <h3>Are capital gains taxed differently in Vermont?</h3>
              <p>
                Vermont generally starts from your federal taxable income, which
                already reflects federal capital gains rules. Vermont may offer
                partial exclusions or adjustments for certain capital gains;
                these are not modeled in detail here.
              </p>

              <h3>Can this calculator handle part‑year residents?</h3>
              <p>
                Not directly. Part‑year and non‑residents often allocate income
                between Vermont and other states using VT‑specific forms. You
                can still use this tool by entering only the portion of income
                you expect to be taxable by Vermont, but the result is only an
                approximation.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I rely on this for filing my Vermont return?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is a <strong>planning and education</strong> tool. For
                filing, use approved tax software, the official Vermont forms
                and instructions, or work with a tax professional.
              </p>
